    {
      "id": "4ce599d313e5d2f9b816d2167a7a77e766ca0e78",
      "author": {
        "_account_id": 104,
        "name": "Niu Yawei",
        "email": "yawei.niu@intel.com",
        "username": "niu",
        "inactive": true
      },
      "date": "2012-10-31 03:01:53.000000000",
      "message": "Patch Set 2:\n\nHi, Andreas\r\n\r\n\"lctl destroy\" was used to destroy the echo object only (we alwasy set the seq as echo seq internally by default), and it's mostly used to \"destory _num_ echo objects from specified objid\".\r\n\r\nThe added 'seq' parameter won't affect the old users, however, if we change the 'objid' to 'fid', current testing scrpits will be broken, I'm not sure if it's a problem should be worried about?",
      "accounts_in_message": [],
      "_revision_number": 2
    },
    {
      "id": "ce790e5110b75ed4c8389d2343d86b68d136a322",
      "author": {
        "_account_id": 147,
        "name": "Maloo",
        "email": "maloo@whamcloud.com",
        "username": "maloo",
        "tags": [
          "SERVICE_USER"
        ]
      },
      "date": "2012-10-31 03:28:47.000000000",
      "message": "Patch Set 2: Fails\n\nTests received by maloo, run on CentOS release 6.3/x86_64: (https://maloo.whamcloud.com/test_sessions/a7e84a3c-2305-11e2-b2a2-52540035b04c).  Ran 14 tests.  4 tests failed: sanity-quota, conf-sanity, replay-single, sanity.",
      "accounts_in_message": [],
      "_revision_number": 2
    },
    {
      "id": "da6ceba42c89c33d8e7c4862a8fae272186e7b88",
      "author": {
        "_account_id": 117,
        "name": "Andreas Dilger",
        "email": "adilger@thelustrecollective.com",
        "username": "adilger"
      },
      "date": "2012-10-31 08:11:59.000000000",
      "message": "Patch Set 2:\n\nNiu,\nwhile the current OSTs only need an objid today, with the landing of DNE code in 2.4 the OSTs will use regular FIDs to identify objects.  So if the interface is changing today to allow sequences, it may as well be able to handle FIDs in the future, especially if using the normal FID format makes it easier to copy FIDs from debug messages.\n\nNote that there is no reason why allowing FIDs as input should break existing scripts, if it allows both a simple objid and a FID as input:\n\n lctl destroy <objid|fid> [num]\n\nwhere \"fid\" is the normal \"0xSEQ:0xOID:0xVER\" format.  This can automatically be detected by something like:\n\n        struct lu_fid fid;\n\n        /* Check for \"0xSEQ:0xOID:0xVER\" first, but if that doesn't work try\n         * for just a single objid for test OST objects for FID_SEQ_ECHO. */\n        if (strstr(argv[1][0], ':') == NULL ||\n            sscanf(argv[1], SFID, RFID(&fid)) != 3)\n                fid.f_seq = FID_SEQ_ECHO;\n                fid.f_oid = strtoull(argv[1], &end, 0);\n                fid.f_ver = 0;\n                if (*end || fid.f_oid == 0 || errno != 0) {\n                        fprintf(stderr, \"error: %s: invalid objid '%s'\\n\",\n                                jt_cmdname(argv[0]), argv[1]);\n                        return CMD_HELP;\n                }\n        }",
      "accounts_in_message": [],
      "_revision_number": 2
    },
    {
      "id": "f4e0c5db959d2f78436fa3479b48c3c073d5f6a7",
      "author": {
        "_account_id": 104,
        "name": "Niu Yawei",
        "email": "yawei.niu@intel.com",
        "username": "niu",
        "inactive": true
      },
      "date": "2012-10-31 08:16:42.000000000",
      "message": "Patch Set 2:\n\nah, right, I'll change it to accept both objid and fid. Thanks.",
      "accounts_in_message": [],
      "_revision_number": 2
    },
